## 3. Data Pipeline Assessment

| Check | Result |
|-------|--------|
| Train clips | 442,460 |
| Train duration | 594.7h |
| Val clips | 17,432 |
| Val duration | 22.4h |
| Missing audio files | 0 (perfect) |
| Speaker overlap train/val | 0 (perfect) |
| Source: CV21 ru | 103,691 clips / 146.0h |
| Source: RuLS | 57,224 clips / 98.2h |
| Source: SOVA RuDevices | 88,661 clips / 89.4h |
| Source: SOVA Audiobooks | 192,884 clips / 261.1h |
| Duration range | 1.0–29.6s |
| Empty texts | 0 |
| Latin-heavy texts | 0 |
| Tokenized manifest | 156,337 entries (cv21+ruls only, generated during M3; SOVA records use on-the-fly tokenization) |

**Assessment:** The data pipeline is clean. All audio files exist, no speaker leakage, no empty texts. The 4-dataset composition is well-balanced. Duration distribution is healthy (mean 4.84s, 95th percentile 9s). The SOVA speaker IDs are pseudo-speakers (MD5 per clip — unavoidable without metadata) which means train/val split is effectively random for those datasets. This is documented and acceptable.

**Note:** `train_tokenized.jsonl` only covers CV21+RULS (156K of 442K entries). SOVA datasets (~281K entries) will be tokenized at runtime via SentencePiece in ASRDataset. This is correct but ~2x slower I/O for those entries. Regenerating the tokenized manifest with all 442K entries would speed up training by avoiding redundant tokenization.

**Gap:** The tokenized manifest only has 156K entries (likely from an earlier stage) vs 442K in the raw train manifest. The `ASRDataset.records` filter is `min_duration <= duration <= max_duration` but the tokenized manifest uses a different filtering approach. This needs investigation before full training.

